Units_Exploration

Vinny Paris

4/15/2021

#Residential Units So to me there appears to be two different models happening. The first is everything up to about 4ish where there is a slow but steady gain. After that though the price seems to become pretty much a flat line for the extremely large values of the residential units. I’m unsure what is happening in that regard but I still tried to fit it

To fit it I used a basic LM where everything before 3.77 was fit with one intercept and slope on log(res_units + 1) and then a secondary intercept and slope for everything past 3.77

## SEL with a single mean only:  18657.06
## SEL with basic LM:  16043.16
## SEL with LM on each side of cutoff point:  15222.59
## Optimal Cutoff Point:  3.77

#Total and Commercial units I do not believe that Total Units or Commercial units are that important. The variance of the commercial units is interesting but I don’t think it matters all that much if we just want to estimate means.

#Odd extreme values As for the massive units they all appear to be coops. I think I know what is happening. So that whole area appears to be one giant co-op (for example in the 3 buildings with the same largest gross square footage is a co-op with apparently two large apartment buildings and a lot of condos/townhouses that apparently form one neighborhood from my googling). Anyway, these people who own an apartment/house in the co-op sell and occasionally information is listed with the co-op statistics (ie you bought a condo with 1200 sqft of living space but since you bought into the co-op its posted as the whole of it having some transaction.)
